Survival analysis can sometimes involve individuals who will not experience the event of interest, forming what is known as the â€œcured groupâ€. Identifying such individuals is not always possible beforehand, as they provide only right-censored data. Ignoring the presence of the cured group can introduce bias in the final model. This paper presents a method for estimating a semiparametric additive hazards model that accounts for the cured fraction. Unlike regression coefficients in a hazard ratio model, those in an additive hazard model measure hazard differences. The proposed method uses a primal-dual interior point algorithm to obtain constrained maximum penalized likelihood estimates of the model parameters, including the regression coefficients and the baseline hazard, subject to certain non-negativity constraints.


Keywords: Additive hazards model; Mixture cure model; Interval censoring; Maximum penalized likelihood estimation;
